Package: rhrg
Type: Package
Title: Individual Tree Crown Delineation by Hierarchical Region Growing
Version: 0.4.0
Authors@R: person("Igor", "Pawelec", email = "igor.pawelec@urk.edu.pl",
                  role = c("aut", "cre"),
                  comment = c(ORCID = "0009-0005-9798-3596"))
Description: Delineates individual tree crowns from a canopy height model.
    Tree tops seed a marker-based watershed; the resulting regions form a
    weighted adjacency graph; crowns then grow under a height-variance
    constraint, merging neighbouring trees where the canopy does not
    separate them, which corrects over-detected tree tops. Canopy claimed by
    two crowns is arbitrated on the data, so the segmentation does not depend
    on the order the tree tops arrive in. Results match the 'pyHRG' Python
    package pixel for pixel on the shared synthetic test suite, and closely
    but not exactly on canopy height models containing plateaus, where the
    two implementations break ties differently; the difference is measured
    and documented rather than assumed away.
    Methods follow Chan, Golub and LeVeque (1983)
    <doi:10.1080/00031305.1983.10483115> for combining region statistics and
    Popescu and Wynne (2004) <doi:10.14358/PERS.70.5.589> for tree detection.
    The pipeline structure derives from 'PyCrown', Zoerner and others (2018)
    <doi:10.7931/M0SR-DN55>.
